It has been shown that saponins from the genus 

Medicago

display fungicidal, molluscicidal, nematicidal, antibacterial, antiviral and antitumoral properties (

; 

). The biological activity of saponins extracted from 

M
. 
sativa

root and aerial system has been extensively investigated to acquire information on their structure–activity relationship (

; 

; 

; 

). The chemical structure certainly plays a key role in the bioactivity of saponins, and the current investigations aim to unravel the specific role of aglycone, as well as the nature and position of the sugar(s) in the molecule. However, these studies have provided contrasting results so far. In some cases there is evidence that sugar moieties play a relevant role, while according to other authors sapogenins are more active (

). The observed antimicrobial activity of alfalfa root saponins against 

Trichoderma viride

indicated that the monodesmoside derivatives of medicagenic acid were more effective than related bidesmosides, even though a direct correlation between number of sugar residues and saponin bioactivity could not be established. In contrast, bioassays with 

Medicago

saponins against human pathogenic fungi and bacteria have highlighted that the presence of sugar residues in the molecule is not determinant for the antibiotic activity (

). It is worth noting that the majority of the reports currently available on 

Medicago

saponins bioactivity is focused on the chemical structure and composition of these compounds, while only few studies have been published on the biological effects. Thus, a specific correlation must be established between saponins and their cellular or subcellular target. For instance, 

, have recently deduced some structural features essential for cytotoxic activity, by carrying out 
in vitro
and preclinical studies carried out with novel synthetic saponins.

In animal cells, saponins target the plasma membrane, binding cholesterol and forming micelle-like aggregates that disrupt membrane functionality and cause lysis. Other cellular targets of saponins in animals are microtubules, endoplasmic reticulum and voltage-dependent anion channels (

). By affecting these cellular components, saponins alter cell cycle progression, with the consequent inhibition of cell proliferation and induction of apoptosis. 

,b, in press) have evidenced that animal and plant cells share common elements in their response to saponins, suggesting for the possible use of plant systems for preliminary large-scale cytotoxicity tests performed on wide collections of natural extracts and/or purified compounds.

Correlation between structure and cytotoxicity of plant saponins have until now led to contrasting results regarding the specific structural requirements for the bioactivity (

; 

). In the present study, the highest activity was observed for saponin containing medicagenic acid, in agreement with the observation that this aglycone was the most toxic to the plant cells, compared to zanhic acid and hederagenin. In addition, our findings suggest that saponin sugar components are important for the activity and that saponins toxicity towards white poplar cells is higher when specific sugars (arabinose, rhamnose and xylose) are present in the molecule. This is well evidenced in the case of zanhic acid (compound 
14
) whose cytotoxicity is enhanced by the addition of the sugar chain AraRhaXyl in saponin 
9
.

Considering the complexity of the molecular events possibly involved in the response of plant cells to the saponin-mediated toxicity, the results hereby presented have been summarized and integrated within a working hypothesis (
Fig. 7
). It is known that the cell wall plays a critical role in sensing biotic/abiotic stresses and in the activation of defence response (

). Pathogen-mediated hydrolysis of the plant cell wall releases oligogalacturonides (OG), as products of pectin partial degradation, that are perceived by the wall-associated Kinase 1 (WAK1) specific receptor (

). WAK1 initiates a signaling pathway consisting of free cytosolic calcium fluctuations, ROS and NO production (

), finally leading to the modulation of defence genes expression (

). Based on the reported data, it is possible that the deleterious effects of alfalfa saponins observed at the cell wall might trigger the above described defence-related signaling pathway. The involvement of ROS and NO in the response of white poplar suspension cultures to saponin extracts from 

M
. 
sativa

had been already highlighted (

), even if the possible target(s) of this signaling pathway in the nuclear compartment are still unknown.

genotoxic activity towards the DNA of white poplar cells, triggering mainly those mechanisms that lead to SSBs accumulation. However, the specific correlation between saponin structure and its genotoxic activity remains unknown. The possible involvement of any cell cycle checkpoints in the response of plant cells to saponins is another key point underlined in 
Fig. 7
. Due to the specific action of alfalfa saponins on the white poplar cell wall, it could be hypothesized that the associated signal cascade might lead to the activation of the so-called ‘Cell Wall Integrity’ checkpoint so far characterized only in yeast (

) and algae (

). In animals, evidence has been provided that different saponin molecules trigger cell cycle arrest at G 
2
/M checkpoint acting on different signaling pathways. 

recently reported the triterpenoid saponin Platycodin can induce cell cycle block at G 
2
/M in Human Glioma cells by decreasing the PI3K/Akt pathway while the triterpene saponin Buddlejasaponin IV (BS-IV) triggers the same response by activating mitochondrial-dependent pathways in human osteosarcoma cells (

). These findings seem to support the idea that different saponin molecules can trigger different signaling pathways, all of them converging at G 
2
/M checkpoint. The cell wall integrity checkpoint is known to regulate cell cycle progression in response to cell wall perturbation resulting from environmental stresses. The involvement of other cell cycle checkpoints cannot be ruled out, as it is known that saponins can target key elements in cell cycle regulation in animal systems (

; 

).

Saponins were extracted and purified as previously described (

; 

, 2009, 2011a). Pure saponins were obtained by a combination of chromatographic separation steps (silica gel open column chromatography and semi-preparative Reversed Phase-High Performance Liquid Chromatography, RP-HPLC) from the crude saponin mixture from leaves and roots of 

M
. 
sativa

L. as described by 

, 2009, 2011a,b). Acid hydrolysis of saponin mixture afforded the related sapogenins that were obtained in a pure 
form after
silica gel open column chromatography (

; 

). Detailed structural elucidation of pure saponins was obtained by Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR) and Electrospray Ionization/Mass Spectrometry (ESI-MS/MS). Sapogenins were also evaluated by Gas Chromatography/Mass Spectrometry (GC/MS) analysis as their methyl-trimethylsilyl derivatives (

; 

, 2009, 2011a; 

). Saponins were dissolved in 30–70% ethanol solution according to their solubility, while sapogenins were dissolved in ethanol and added at the indicated concentration to white poplar cell cultures.
